SIMPLE: intercede
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intercede
<hw>In`ter*cede"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Interceded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Interceding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>intercedere</ets>,
<ets>intercessum</ets>; <ets>inter</ets> between + <ets>cedere</ets> to
pass: cf. F. <ets>interc⟦eacute⟧der</ets>. See <er>Cede</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass between; to intervene.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He supposed that a vast period <qex>interceded</qex> between that
origination and the age wherein he lived.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M.
Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act between parties with a view to reconcile
differences; to make intercession; to beg or plead in behalf of another;
to mediate; -- usually followed by <ptcl>with</ptcl> and
<ptcl>for</ptcl> or <ptcl>on behalf of</ptcl>; <as>as, I will
<ex>intercede with</ex> him <ex>for</ex> you</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I to the lords will <qex>intercede</qex>, not doubting⟦br⟧
Their favorable ear.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To mediate; arbitrate. See
<er>Interpose</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intercede</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intercede
<hw>In`ter*cede"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To be, to come, or to pass,
between; to separate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir I.
Newton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intercedence</ent>⟦br⟧
